'''Marion Grice''' (born April 10, 1992) is an [[American football]] [[running back]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Arizona State Sun Devils football|Arizona State]].

==Early Years==
Grice attended [[Nimitz High School (Harris County, Texas)|Chester W. Nimitz High School]] in [[Schertz, Texas]]. He graduated in 2010. 

==College career==
Grice attended [[Blinn College|Blinn Community College]] for two years. He totaled 2,221 rushing yards and 33 touchdowns over two junior college seasons at Blinn, and was named as a Second-Team [[NJCAA]] [[All-America]]n as a sophomore in 2011 after carrying 174 times for 1,052 yards with 16 rushing touchdowns. Rated as a four-star recruit by ''[[Rivals.com]]'', he was listed as the No. 5 overall junior college prospect in the country.<ref>[http://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/player-Marion-Grice-119939 Marion Grice - Yahoo Sports]</ref>

He committed to [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]] on February 1, 2012.<ref>[http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2012/02/01/20120201asu-football-marion-grice-recruiting.html Junior college running back commits to ASU football]</ref>

In 2012, working his way as the starter, he led the team in rushing yards with 679 yards on 103 rushes (6.6 avg) and had 11 touchdowns. He also added 41 receptions for 425 yards and eight touchdowns. He finished his season recording 159 yards on 14 rushes and two touchdowns, being named [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]] of the [[2012 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl]].<ref>[http://www.statepress.com/2012/12/29/grice-overcomes-tragedy-to-deliver-for-asu-in-bowl-game/ Grice overcomes tragedy to deliver for ASU in bowl game]</ref> In 2013, he rushed for 996 yards on 191 rushes (5.2 avg) and 14 touchdowns, and also caught 50 passes for 438 yards and six touchdowns. He earned second-team All-[[Pacific-12 Conference|Pac-12]] honors.<ref>[http://www.houseofsparky.com/2013/12/2/5167414/pac-12-all-conference-asu-football-will-sutton ASU Football: 13 Sun Devils named All-Pac-12 Conference selections]</ref>

